<font color="#FF0000">GI-ANTI WAR MOVEMENT</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec 28  7:08:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Concerning Spitting on returning troups:<br><br>
Each person fighting for their cause (soldier or <br>
anti-war protester) did what they thought was right<br>
at the time. With hind sight we may now know it was<br>
wrong. If every bullet hit a &quot;proper&quot; target, if every<br>
protest action was politically correct, things would be<br>
different. They were not. Some bullets killed innocent<br>
people. Vets have to live with that, and we, the non-vets<br>
need to understand the reasons, and hold those accountable<br>
who were the creators of the war, not the grunts who<br>
were there for a million different reasons. Protesters<br>
have to live with the fact that we did spit on vets, and<br>
treated them as less than human upon their return. Vets<br>
need to understand that this was out of a frustration<br>
due to our inability to stop what we considered to be<br>
an illegal and immoral war. We at home were lied to,<br>
beat up, arrested, had our lives disrupted, were spyed<br>
upon, had our parents and family harrassed, killed<br>
and so on. It is a shame that the war caused us all to<br>
do things that inother times we would never have done. <br>

